00:52:53.430 --> 00:52:56.340
AUDIENCE: If you can choose
what's your favorite book

00:52:56.340 --> 00:52:57.300
that you've written.

00:52:57.300 --> 00:52:57.870
SALMAN RUSHDIE:
That I've written?

00:52:57.870 --> 00:53:00.860
AUDIENCE: Yeah, also what's the
favorite one that you've read,

00:53:00.860 --> 00:53:02.510
assuming they're not the same.

00:53:02.510 --> 00:53:04.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:04.010 --> 00:53:06.860
SALMAN RUSHDIE: I
don't actually read

00:53:06.860 --> 00:53:09.280
the novels of Salman Rushdie.

00:53:09.280 --> 00:53:11.220
I just write them.

00:53:11.220 --> 00:53:14.470
By the time I
finished writing them,

00:53:14.470 --> 00:53:17.570
I've read them so many
times that I never

00:53:17.570 --> 00:53:21.890
want to look at them again,
because in the process

00:53:21.890 --> 00:53:25.340
of writing a book, you reread,
and reread, and reread.

00:53:25.340 --> 00:53:28.450
And by the time the book has
gone through the publication

00:53:28.450 --> 00:53:32.550
period, you read it again in
great detail dozens of times,

00:53:32.550 --> 00:53:35.720
and at the end of
that, I'm done with it.

00:53:38.720 --> 00:53:40.680
I have to say I'm really
delighted with the way

00:53:40.680 --> 00:53:42.530
in which this book is
being received so far.

00:53:42.530 --> 00:53:45.970
People seem to be really
enjoying it and having

00:53:45.970 --> 00:53:49.180
a great time with it, and
that's a very nice feeling.

00:53:49.180 --> 00:53:52.380
And there are these
two earlier books

00:53:52.380 --> 00:53:56.860
that I wrote for my two sons
when they were 11 or 12 years

00:53:56.860 --> 00:54:00.260
old each, "Haroun and
the Sea of Stories,

00:54:00.260 --> 00:54:04.200
and "Luka and the Fire of Life,"
which one is the sort of sequel

00:54:04.200 --> 00:54:06.620
to the other.

00:54:06.620 --> 00:54:08.840
And I have a very
soft spot for those,

00:54:08.840 --> 00:54:12.530
partly because they were written
in this very personal way,

00:54:12.530 --> 00:54:16.160
and again, partly because I just
had the most fun writing them.

00:54:16.160 --> 00:54:18.260
They were really--
I can see why people

00:54:18.260 --> 00:54:22.990
who write children's books
go around looking happy,

00:54:22.990 --> 00:54:24.570
because it's kind of fun.

00:54:24.570 --> 00:54:28.470
And also the response you
get from young readers

00:54:28.470 --> 00:54:32.990
is incredibly enjoyable.

00:54:32.990 --> 00:54:36.490
I get these letters from
entire classrooms who've

00:54:36.490 --> 00:54:38.640
been reading
"Haroun," or "Luka,"

00:54:38.640 --> 00:54:41.220
and they've all done
drawings of the characters.

00:54:41.220 --> 00:54:44.700
And they write me notes saying
which characters they like,

00:54:44.700 --> 00:54:47.050
and which ones they
don't like, and giving me

00:54:47.050 --> 00:54:52.720
tips for how to write sequels,
what that should be about.

00:54:52.720 --> 00:54:55.470
It's really a lot of fun.

00:54:55.470 --> 00:54:58.780
I had this letter
from a girl in America

00:54:58.780 --> 00:55:02.990
in Massachusetts when
"Haroun" came out,

00:55:02.990 --> 00:55:04.610
and she asked me
various questions.

00:55:04.610 --> 00:55:08.490
She was obviously quite a
smart, highly literate reader.

00:55:08.490 --> 00:55:11.220
So she had a quite intelligent
letter, and at the end of it,

00:55:11.220 --> 00:55:14.120
it said, please write back.

00:55:14.120 --> 00:55:15.665
Please reply to
this letter at once.

00:55:15.665 --> 00:55:18.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:18.630 --> 00:55:20.790
She said, because
when I grew up,

00:55:20.790 --> 00:55:24.755
I intend to be either a writer
myself or a world leader.

00:55:24.755 --> 00:55:27.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:27.090 --> 00:55:29.590
I thought right
back to this girl.

00:55:29.590 --> 00:55:33.220
She's going to be
president in 20 years time.

00:55:33.220 --> 00:55:35.660
So anyway, those books,
I think, I would choose.

00:55:35.660 --> 00:55:38.140
If I had to choose,
I would choose those

00:55:38.140 --> 00:55:41.140
just because it's been so
much fun to be their author

00:55:41.140 --> 00:55:43.620
because of what's
come back at me.

00:55:43.620 --> 00:55:45.531
CHRISTINA MATTEOTTI: Fantastic.

